dsiter.pipe

Interface IPipe

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    FilterPipe, FirstPipe, LastPipe, RenamePipe, SkipPipe, SkipWhilePipe, StridePipe, TakePipe, TakeWhilePipe, ZipPipe

    public interface IPipe
    Interface representing a pipe operation to a future iterator. Pipe operations are conceptually similar to pipes in shell scripting: they take the output of one iterator and make it the input to another iterator.

    Pipe instances in dsiter are type-specific: they encode all of the information required to make a specific type of transforming iterator, except for the source iterator to be transformed. The source iterator is supplied later by calling attachTo(dsiter.iterator.IDatasetIterator).

    A Pipe can also be considered a partial application of an iterator (similar to currying in functional programming): it specifies everything that the constructor needs except for the source iterator.

    For example, a StridePipe contains all of the information required to make a StrideIterator except for the source iterator. An actual instance of StrideIterator is not constructed, however, until a source iterator is passed via attachTo.

      • attachTo

        IDatasetIterator attachTo(IDatasetIterator src)
        Attach this pipe to the passed source iterator. This will usually construct a new iterator that uses src as its source, but the actual method is not explicitly specified.
        Parameters:
        src - The source iterator
        Returns:
        An iterator with this pipe attached to it (conceptually, if not necessarily physically)
